When asked in an online interview on Monday by Japanese news outlet, Mainichi, whether he will play for Kashiwa next season, Olunga replied he still has a contract with Reysol.
“I don't want to talk about transfers or anything like that. Now, I'm working hard for Reysol as a member of Reysol.”
His contract was supposed to end on January 31, 2021, but Kashiwa moved with speed to tie him down with a new two-year contract. Olunga’s new improved contract at Kashiwa lapses on January 31, 2023, but that has not stopped him being linked with moves out of Japan.





With the mid-season transfer window for the ‘Big Five’ European leagues (Spanish La Liga, English Premier League, Italian Serie A, German Bundesliga and French Ligue 1) opening on January 1, 2021, any club will have to part with huge fees to get the services of the lethal striker “if he changes his mind”.    
Love for Arsenal
Local football enthusiasts have urged Olunga to move to Europe. He was even linked with moves to Turkey and France in the last European transfer window.





Michael Olunga during a past match.
Photo credit: Pool


Kenyans are huge followers of the English Premier League and hoping to see Olunga on their television screens, they have for two years been urging him to ditch the Japanese league saying “it is not competitive”.



